General FAQ

This document is a community driven full breakdown of the respective class. This is a live document where we actively change it based on feedback and changes to the game to provide the best information to the community. The majority of us hang around in the Community Lost Ark Discord in our respective class channels. If you would like to give us feedback or ask questions contact us there.

Why should I play this class?

Being the only male Martial Artist, Striker is a dynamic melee back attacker with great visuals, sound effects and skills.

It’s varied in its gameplay with several different ways to approach end game content and will keep you coming back for more.

How does my identity work?

Our identity consists in building the orbs seen above, using skills commonly designated as generators, and using these orbs as a resource to cast powerful attacks that deal massive damage, commonly known as spenders.

How do I decide on a build?

Both have their strengths and weaknesses. It’s a matter of personal preference.

Here’s a short summary of the builds. For further information, read their respective

sections of this document.

Deathblow

Esoteric Flurry

Summary

Build 4 orbs, dump 1 spender, repeat

Fast paced stream of spenders

Pros

  • Low APM, less uptime needed
  • High survivability
  • “Burst” damage, big hits
  • Downtime allows for repositioning
  • Fast paced
  • Access to more synergy
  • High move/attack speed
  • Better stagger/destruction

Cons

  • Very high requirements
  • Very slow movement
  • Low stagger/destruction
  • Specialization build
  • Punished by downtime
  • Lower per hit damage
  • High APM and lots of ass chase
  • 5 Spender has a high skill floor

What are my Party Synergies?

Synergies are a buff your party benefits from. These only apply to your party and not the entire raid. Consistent synergies are up for most of the fight while Burst synergies are much more infrequent.

What are the key pieces of my build?

Runes

Striker is all about building orbs, and Wealth runes are a core part of that process. Deathblow specifically needs a high investment in terms of runes. It's recommended for those with not many runes collected to play swift centered Esoteric Flurry instead.

Accessories

Striker needs high quality accessories for the most part. While some swiftness Esoteric builds don't care too much, Deathblow, 4 Spender 4/9/10 and 5 spender really benefit from high quality pieces, as specialization breakpoints start playing a role in your build.

Why does Striker use Fate of the Lazeniths + Three Umar Families card set?

Three Umar Families: Back attack damage to foes +2% (6 awakening) + Back attack damage to foes +10% (15 awakening)

Fate of the Lazeniths: Elemental damage +2% (4 awakening) + Successful attacks create a chance of all Elemental Damage +24% for 8s (10 awakening)

Striker can utilize these two card set because most if not all of Striker abilities have the back-attack affix so these abilities get affected by the Three Umar Families set.

For Fate of the Lazeniths set  Lightning Tiger Strike, Tiger Emerges,  Blast Formation, and  Sweeping Kick and Flash Heat Fang are all elemental.

Deathblow

Written by Eph

 

Playstyle

Deathblow is the class engraving that massively amplifies Striker's damage on Esoteric skills. It is a back-attack reliant and specialization-based playstyle that focuses on doing huge damage with fewer Spenders.

Build 4 Orbs, and send out a nuke, repeat.

Stat Allocation

There is nothing noteworthy about deathblow stat distribution, full spec is the only real way to go. Please refrain from going crit ring. I know it's cheaper but just don’t.

Bracelets

There's not much to add on the topic of bracelets. The most important aspect is a high spec roll to make sure you hit your breakpoints. Crit is nice to have but less of a priority. Beneficial effects include Ambush, Fervor, Circulate, Wedge, etc.

Rotation

Deathblow’s rotation consists in a rather simple sequence of 2 builders into 1 spender on repeat, the following flowchart describes how an ideal cycle should look like

Opener

Allows for 3 rapid Adrenaline Stacks, do it every time you (re)engage the boss without stacks. Read

3 Spender


*optional for extra orb on BF
If you need to auto attack for meter, do it before BF and after VT

2 Spender

Stagger

*Save 2 orbs beforehand if possible


In depth look

Fights aren't always simple and situations arise where keeping up the above order might not be possible, and so it's important to understand the principles of how the class is played so you know what to do when it all goes off the rails.

Before we get into it, please also check out the Striker Specialization Calculator, which will tell you exactly how many orbs your combos generate and how many auto attacks you might need for certain thresholds.

The 2 main orb generation combos are:

SSB +LW  and  VT +MFK


You can split these 4 generators into 2 ‘’groups’’:
The ‘’Small Generators’’  SSB and VTD

And the ‘’Big Generators’’ LW and MFK

When correctly set up, each of them should be interchangeable, so you should be able to think of these combos as 2 groups that can be mixed and matched to generate 4 Esoteric Orbs.

As said above, any combination of small+big generators should result in 4 Esoteric Orbs. If you are not able to generate 4 Orbs from a particular combo, consider adjusting your wealth runes or increasing your spec by opting for higher quality accessories.

       

 SSB is much faster than VTD and provides an attack speed buff, furthermore you want LW to lead into your hardest hitting ability, LTS, to guarantee it's affected by the crit buff.

 As such it's always preferable to SSB +LW into LTS.


It's also good to keep in mind that VTF should precede MFK so it goes on cooldown sooner, so there is less downtime when using VTF again to generate orbs for BF.

At the end of your first 2 spenders(, ), you'll be left with SSB, VT and SDK to generate orbs for your BF. This period of your cycle is highly flexible and you don't always need to generate 4 orbs for it, nor will the situation always allow for it.

Ideally BF will never delay LTS. As such, the amount of orbs you can generate for BF will be contingent on this window. Don’t overcommit to it, sometimes you will have to send it with 3 orbs, even 2. Some situations will result in you not even casting BF if LTS is coming back up due to mechanics.

In scenarios where time is not a worry, SSB first so it comes back up as soon as possible, into SDK and VTD, auto attacking to fill 4 orbs if necessary in your setup.

In regards to the LW crit buff window, under ideal, i.e Trixion scenarios, both LTS and TE will land inside the buff timer, but in reality, you'll be faced with several situations where only your LTS will land inside this window. It's normal, don't sweat it.

Tips and Tricks

This section will delve into small optimizations you can do and also discuss some small build variations you might want to try.

Adrenaline optimization

Adrenaline is a key component of our kit, white number bad. As such we must always be looking to maximize our time at max Adrenaline stacks.

 As lightly mentioned in the rotation table, we open combat by casting all 3 chains of SDK, giving us 3 stacks, followed up by SSB, LW and

LTS resulting in a perfect buildup of 6 stacks right as we hit our LTS.

Looking something like this:

To maintain Adrenaline stacks during sections of the fight where you have downtime for whatever reason, you can cast SDK and delay each subsequent recast by up to 2 seconds, extending the duration on your Adrenaline stacks by up to 6 seconds. You can also follow this up with SSB or VTD to extend it further in extreme cases, but this might have a negative impact on your rotation later, so do it with care.

TE and LTS angles

One of the main advantages of using the Ascension tripod for TE, is its wide area of attack, which enables you to pull off very sketchy back attacks from angles you might not expect. This is also possible for LTS where you can angle your hit in a way that clips the back attack hitbox while your character just continues onwards. Both of these tricks require practice and experience but can really help out in a fight. Here are a couple examples:

MFK Distance

A very important concept you should master about your striker, is the different ranges at which you can hit your MFK for different amounts of orb generation. These are the so-called close, medium and far range MFK.

As exemplified in the video below you can see how MFK can hit from 1 up to 3 times, depending on what range you cast it from. This can impact your rune choices and facilitate certain situations where you might have to gap close with MFK and follow it up with either

VTD or SSB depending on what combo gives you 4 orbs at a determined distance.

BF into LW

It's worth noting there's a small trick you can do depending on the situation and if the cooldowns/positioning lines up, where you follow up on BF with LW instead of SSB, so that the flame explosions from the tripod benefits from the crit buff, so you would do >+ and proceed with normal rotation from there. Which looks something like this:

This video is taken from Trixion with Spirit Absorption lvl2 to emulate having a support with yearning, without it, it becomes harder to fit TE into the LW crit window.

 This is not mandatory and might even cost you more than it gains. Generally to do this you need to be sure you will get full value from the BF ticks as it can compromise your TE damage.

Focus Hit VT

 Violent Tiger Dance has the Focus Hit tripod that makes the animation faster, smoother and overall better to play with, at the cost of less meter generation.

The setups to play with this tripod are heavy in requirements. Without Enlightenment roll on your bracelet, you will need all the tripods, Wealth runes  and 1836 spec to play it without auto attacks, but even then if you far MFK you will have to auto a lot. Fortunately far MFK’ing is relatively rare.

The Wealth setup is as follows:

I wouldn't recommend anyone below 1820 spec to even attempt to play like this, but if you have and Enlightenment roll on your bracelet or want to see exactly how many auto attacks you would need in various situations, please use the Specialization Breakpoint Calculator

White Tiger Kick SDK

SDK has a level 10 tripod called White Tiger Kick that makes the animation very slightly faster and cooler. For this you need to drop all generator skills to level 10, maintaining level 12 only on the 3 spenders, and pumping SDK to level 10.

DPS Distribution

This is the approximate damage distribution you'll see as a 3 Spender Deathblow Striker. Blast Formation will vary wildly from 15% up to 25% of your damage depending on how good of a pull/fight it is for it.

“Etc” is comprised mostly of VTD and MFK. Awakening does about 2% of your damage.

The darker region of the BF bar represents the portion of damage over time component from the Flame Explosion tripod.

Can you explain gem levels better?

Damage

Deathblow uses 3 Damage gems. LTS is your most important gem, followed by TE. You can settle for a lower level BF gem, as it's a smaller portion of your damage.

Upgrade them in that order, as your budget allows.

Cooldown

Here things start getting a little more complex. These gems don't result in directly higher numbers but they allow for flexibility, freedom and smoothness that increases your DPS indirectly.

The biggest factor for a smooth rotation is a level 10 BF cooldown gem.

This skill is the limiting factor for a smoother rotation, and even a level 10 gem won't fix it entirely. If you intend to play Striker even half seriously, it's recommended you invest in this gem.

That said, the class will work completely fine with a level 7.

It is very recommended you invest in a level 10 cooldown gem for BF.

Following this, VT and SSB are your second most important cooldown gems, as they allow you to cycle into BF smoothly and reduce overall downtime if you have to reposition or make a mistake. There's no clear level you need for these gems, of course 10 is always ideal but even a 9, especially on VT can make a noticeable difference.

Leaving these at level 7 is fine, but 9+ will feel noticeably better.

LW and LTS are your 3rd most important cooldown gems. Here the situation is a little different as these skills are nearly always coupled together, and their cooldown is a little too similar. This means that if you have matching level gems, LW will be off cooldown a little too early, resulting in about a 0.5s gap between LW and LTS. This can be a bit annoying.

This is not a reason to undervalue running 10s on both, but just to point out that having a slightly higher level LTS gem can feel smoother. Usually 1-2 levels is enough.

Leaving LW at 7 is fine, LTS is recommended a little higher

Finally SDK, MFK and TE are mostly personal preference. These won't affect rotation smoothness at all, and mostly help with faster mistake correction and generally more flexibility in your rotation.

Leaving these at 7 is fine.

Do I need the Wealth runes?

Short answer, yes.

Long answer is you really need at least 1 Wealth,  1 Wealth and 2 Wealth runes. It's very much ideal to have 2 Wealth runes.

This is of course assuming you are looking to develop your striker and play a 3 spender setup.

More information on what to do if you only have 1 Wealth further below.

If your roster has many strikers and wardancers, or you only care about your striker, maybe you should rush LazUmar, but if you care about your overall roster more, Los30 is the usual bet.

How much stagger does Striker do?

Striker Stagger (Data from Hako@inven.co.kr, graph by Bhout)

Which is better, Deathblow or Esoteric Flurry?
Nonsensical question, both have different playstyles with different strengths and can perform as well as their pilot makes them perform.

Play what you enjoy.

Should I switch from Eso to Deathblow?
Only if you feel like you'd get more enjoyment from playing Deathblow.
We can't pick your build for you but ultimately you have to consider that in general, you can gear like 1 to 10 Esoteric Strikers for the price of one Deathblow, so if you're considering the swap, make sure you save up a considerable amount.

When Should I swap to 3 spender?

A lot of people wonder when they should start playing 3 spender.

You should be able to generate 4 orbs from the 2 ability combos.

SSB/VT + LW/MFK

At that point you can safely start running BF, even if you can only cast it with 2 orbs

Is there a recommended minimum spec for 3 spender?

What we could call ‘’minimum viable product’’ would be:

  • Level 5 orb generation tripod for SSB
  • Level 4 orb generation tripods for LW and MFK
  • At Least 1640 spec (including pet buff)
  • Access to 1 Wealth (),  1 Wealth () and 2 Wealth (+)

This allows for a 4 orb LTS, a 4 orb TE and a 3 Orb BF without SDK.

I can’t generate 4 orbs for Blast Formation but I want to, what do I need?

For more accurate info tailored to your setup, please use the breakpoint spreadsheet.

There are 2 ways to generate 4 Orbs for BF, with no auto attacks

At  1647 Spec (including pet buff) you need

  • Level 5 orb generation tripods on LW and SSB
  •  1 Legendary, 2 Purple and 2 Blue Wealth runes.

With the following Wealth rune distribution:

 Wealth on VT, Wealth on both  SSB and SDK, Wealth MFK and LW

At  1802 Spec (including pet buff) you need

  • Level 5 orb generation tripods on LW and SSB
  •  1 Legendary, 1 Purple and 2 Blue Wealth runes.

With the following Wealth rune distribution:

 Wealth on VT, Wealth on both  SSB, Wealth MFK and LW

This allows you to generate 4 Orbs for BF with SSB + VTD + SDK, without the need for the Wealth rune on SDK.

If you are at this point, consider placing your second Wealth on MFK if it wasn't already (if you have it), as this allows you the extra flexibility of generating 4 orbs even if you long range MFK.

More info about MFK distance here.

Is it worth casting Blast Formation with 3 orbs instead of 4?

Depends on the situation, don't overthink it, it's better to hit a 3 orb BF than to miss a 4 Orb and dick over your rotation.

Spec items are expensive, can i run a crit [insert item here] instead?

Not ideal.

You can potentially offset the loss of spec by running 2 spender with SK as an extra generation tool, or by getting a good bracelet with high spec when that becomes an option, but overall you should avoid doing this. The unfortunate reality is that Deathblow is an expensive class to build, and while no one will stop you from doing this, you will be limiting the power and flow of your character and never reaching its true potential.

I can't get X orbs for my X skill, should I run Esoteric Extortion on SDK?

No, SDK with Excellent Mobility is half of your movement options, it's really not worth giving it up for a little more orb generation, just fix your stuff man.

Does our rotation change if you have Lazenith+Umar card set??

Not really, we don't want to play around the Lazenith buff as it is an RNG proc, and micromanaging it usually leads to more harm than gain for your DPS.

Just focus on developing a sort of internal timer so you know when it's more or less of cooldown and can avoid doing random actions that will proc it too soon or too late such as auto attacks or SDK into the boss.

Don't worry if it falls off sync, it will naturally line up over the course of the fight due to fight mechanics.

Can I do double class engraving?

No.

Esoteric Flurry

Written by Lucas

Playstyle

Esoteric Flurry is a fast paced class focused on dealing bursts of damage consisting of multiple spenders. Contrary to the build one, spend one philosophy of Deathblow, Esoteric Flurry can unload many spenders in a row and deal an astounding amount of damage while looking very cool doing it.

It is a very build diverse engraving that can caters well to people who like to tinker with their setups.

Build Explanation

This guide offers a selection of builds that have an impact on everything from stat allocation to runes and tripod choices, as such this section is designed to give you an initial insight into how the builds differ.

4 Spender MFK

Default setup, low barrier to entry and fast paced, very flexible

Relies on the skill Moon Flash Kick, which can be wonky to use.

4 Spender (4/9/10)

4/9/10 refers to the stat spread, 400ish Crit / 900ish Spec / 1000ish Swift.
Main benefit being the removal of MFK, which lets you add another skill for mobility or damage. Higher barrier to entry than 4 Spender MFK, and more strict on meter management.

5 Spender

Very high damage at the cost of all swiftness. It's strict on meter management, uptime requirements and adaptability.

it's expensive to build and hard to play well, but it pumps.

3 Spender (FHF & VT)

In the same way 4 Spender 4/9/10 removes MFK, 3 spender goes a step further and also removes CotWG, a spender many find annoying to deal with.
Only running 3 spenders, this build benefits the least from building Esoteric Flurry 3

Esoteric Flurry sports many different builds, with different stats and different combinations to achieve the desired stat spread.

In depth look

More than just the sequence of skills to use, it's important to understand why you're using them in the order above, so that you understand the principles and know how to adapt to situations that force you out of this comfort zone.

4 Spender MFK

Not much needs to be said here, LW opens up a crit buff window and you try to fit all you can in that window, regardless of what actually ends up fitting, and you wait to repeat it again.

 Once you’re well geared you will typically have extra orbs. This will lead into dynamic combos where you will want to dump some orbs after SSB so you don't over generate and waste orbs. You can cast BF after SSB and proceed with your

LW cycle, letting BF benefit from extra crit.


You have a lot of extra abilities to play with and once you get tripods for MFK and high spec through quality/horizontal completion, you will have a very forgiving playstyle as a striker where missing non spender isn’t as detrimental for burst cycles making prog content very forgiving.

4 Spender (4/9/10)

Similarly to the previous build, the principle is the same, cram as much as you can in LW buff and use weaker abilities outside of it.

SHD and SDK are great tools to close the gap and position initially, and by the time your LW window is over, you'll likely need to reposition with these tools as well.


You can also slightly change how you approach your cycle, depending on how ballsy you're feeling:

Most practical

Has 1st priority on LTS (largest portion of your damage)
Highest burst

Has most spenders within LW debuff window

Has Great Explosion + Flame Explosion of BF during LW debuff and more time for CotWG

Remember that starting a rotation in any manner of sequence means locking yourself into doing that sequence of skills until you get a soft cooldown reset from something like boss phasing or mechanics that forces downtime. Hence the practical rotation being the recommended way to go.

5 Spender

5 Spender rotations are flexible, yet rigid,mainly because of SI.

We can break it down into a few “core” principles:

1- LW window is very important and must fit LTS and TE

2- Each cycle should have 1 cast of LTS, TE, BF and CotWG

2- Each cycle must cast SI twice.

While simple on the surface, these 3 rules quickly become hard to juggle as the chaos of a boss fight progresses.

Here is a breakdown of the “why” the skills are ordered as they are

  • Ideally BF is cast before LW so the explosions benefit from the crit.

  • LW needs to fit LTS and TE. That's the main rule that doesn't change regardless of what else you do.

  • After this point what happens next is where you show how good of a player you are, essentially. The goal here is to be able to fit CotWG and 2 SI casts before BF comes back up.

This can look like this for example:
...

Or maybe like this:

...

Or even:

You get the idea. There's no magic one size fits all advice here, it will come from a place of practice and experience, as SI casts are what truly tells a good and a great Striker apart.

For your opener it's mostly the same but you use SDK first to stack Adrenaline into SSB BF LW and proceed with normal rotation from there, as otherwise if you slot an SI cast in the opener you will not have enough orbs for a smooth first cycle, as such the opener looks like this:

3 Spender

Once again, same thing as before, fit what you can in the crit window, cast the rest and repeat.

 Your first burst cycle is  LW,  SSB,  LTS, TE,  VTD (*If low spec use VTD before TE, so you have enough orbs).

Reposition with  SDK as necessary and SSB for attack speed, rotating into  BF followed by  FHF.

 If you’re a Raid Capitan and/or Mass Increase build maintaining attack/movement speed through Rage OR  SSB is  very important.

  FHF does not care about  LW crit debuff,  as this skill has built in crit rate, and you can spacebar out of the animation.

One of the glaring issues of 3 spender is the requirements on orb generation. If you do not feel comfortable with your rotations then you will face issues.

Please do trixion tests to work out the kinks in your build by troubleshooting tripods and wealth runes. You can easily sustain bubbles with landing all skills after 500 spec with wealth runes as long as you understand playstyle and cycles.

Use the Specialization Breakpoint Calculator

If you need more help on figuring out exactly where to place wealth runes.

Tips and Tricks

This section will delve into small optimizations you can do and also discuss some small build variations you might want to try.

Adrenaline optimization

Adrenaline is a key component of our kit, white number bad. As such we must always be looking to maximize our time at max Adrenaline stacks.

 As lightly mentioned in the rotation table, we open combat by casting all 3 chains of SDK, giving us 3 stacks, followed up by SSB, LW and

LTS resulting in a perfect buildup of 6 stacks right as we hit our LTS.

Looking something like this:

To maintain Adrenaline stacks during sections of the fight where you have downtime for whatever reason, you can cast SDK and delay each subsequent recast by up to 2 seconds, extending the duration on your Adrenaline stacks by up to 6 seconds. You can also follow this up with SSB or VTD to extend it further in extreme cases, but this might have a negative impact on your rotation later, so do it with care.

TE and LTS angles

One of the main advantages of using the Ascension tripod for TE, is its wide area of attack, which enables you to pull off very sketchy back attacks from angles you might not expect. This is also possible for LTS where you can angle your hit in a way that clips the back attack hitbox while your character just continues onwards. Both of these tricks require practice and experience but can really help out in a fight. Here are a couple examples:

MFK Distance

A very important concept you should master about your striker, is the different ranges at which you can hit your MFK for different amounts of orb generation. These are the so-called close, medium and far range MFK.

As exemplified in the video below you can see how MFK can hit from 1 up to 3 times, depending on what range you cast it from. This can impact your rune choices and facilitate certain situations where you might have to gap close with MFK and follow it up with either VTD or SSB depending on what combo gives you 4 orbs at a determined distance.

5 Spender CotWG Lazenith optimization

A niche thing you can optimize if you're a nerd and LazUmar user, is running a CD gem on CotWG instead of SDK or TE. This is useful if you want to take better advantage of a Lazenith proc to fit CotWG  where you’d usually cast an SI:

...

This last CotWG will have about 2 seconds of cooldown remaining if you don't have a gem, making it miss the Lazenith proc.

This is a highly niche and rare scenario.

What’s special about this build?

This build removes MFK for a shorter Spender rotation.
This allows for an optional 8th skill for damage or utility.
This build is also known as the Drift Striker build when utilizing SHD.

What’s the best 8th skill to run?

SHD effectively grants you another dash on a 6s cooldown.

FHF and VTD both do similar damage, weighted towards the former.
FHF is a mid-high stagger skill with Weak point Lv.1 and doesn't need to land in the LW window.
VTD’s damage is very reliant on critting, so it needs to land in the LW window. It is better suited for a 5/8/10 stat spread

An 8th damage skill is obviously more DPS but a utility skill might make your damage more consistent, and it looks way cooler too.

Are there any important breakpoints or thresholds?

You'll need Lv. 5 Abundant Resources on SSB.

841 Specialization = Any Rune on SDK, Epic Wealth on LW, Legendary Wealth on SSB

782 Specialization = Rare Wealth on SDK, Epic Wealth on LW, Legendary Wealth on SSB

753 Specialization = Epic Wealth on SDK, Epic Wealth on LW, Legendary Wealth on SSB

>1000 Swift with Lv. 8 SSB CD gem for rotation smoothness

(3 Orbs)(1 Orb)

Can I dump Swift below 1000?
Yes, under one of two circumstances; If you run VTD, you can drop Swiftness for more Specialization or Crit, or if you have a Lv. 9-10 SSB CD gem. It mostly affects your rotation smoothness, so try it in Trixion.

Any additional options?
If you drop TE Quick Prep to Lv. 1, you can run Swift Footwork Lv. 5 on SSB for a faster animation, but shorter range. Works well for burst windows, since you use this skill twice per rotation.

How does this build compare to the other builds?

4 Spender SHD performs roughly the same as 4 Spender MFK, but with more mobility/shorter burst

4 Spender FHF/VTD performs with a slightly higher damage ceiling than 4 Spender MFK

5 Spender has the highest damage ceiling.

5 Spender FAQ

What’s special about this build?

Highest damage Esoteric Flurry and arguably Striker build. It uses 5 Spenders and relies on back attacking all of them along with high uptime to dish out a lot of damage.

 This also means that it’s a build that is difficult to play at its maximum potential.

Are there any breakpoints to consider?

This build can work at 3 different Spec breakpoints, which in turn also changes what LW tripods you use:

1719 Specialization:

  

                Lv.1

1501 Specialization:

  

                Lv.1

1400 Specialization:

  

                Lv.5

Pick one tripod
To drop to Lv.1

 /  /

What’s the best amount of spec to have?

What stat spread you should aim for is generally dictated by whichever spec breakpoint you're interested in.

More crit is usually more damage

1719+ gains attack speed synergy
1501+ loses synergy but gains crit

1400+ loses a tripod but gains a lot of crit


The general idea is you want to hit whatever breakpoint you want and dump the rest into crit, provided you are not surpassing 100% crit

Do you have rotation smoothness tips?

Since this build drops LWQuick Prep to Lv. 1, it is preferable your BF and LW CD gems to be the same level, in order to have a smooth rotation.

If you do not have TE Quick Prep Lv. 5, you should use a CD gem on TE

Any alternative setups?

Running Quick Prep to Lv. 1 and a CD gem on TE  instead of SDK allows you to run Swift Footwork Lv. 5 on SSB, a good quality of life tripod.

Can you explain gem levels better?

Damage

Esoteric Flurry uses up to 5 Damage gems.

LTS is your most important gem, followed by TE.

You can settle for a lower level BF and Nado gem, as these are less consistent skills.

SI, MFK, VT and FHF are very small portions of your damage and it is recommended you upgrade these last, if at all.

Cooldown

Not all cooldown gems will be mentioned, this is because some genuinely don't play a big role in how the class feels. If you don't see a particular cooldown gem mentioned, it means it's fine to leave it at level 7.

The biggest factor for a smooth rotation is a level 10 BF cooldown gem.

Regardless if you're a Swiftness or Specialization player, this skill is the limiting factor for a smoother rotation. If you play this class seriously, invest in this.

That said, the class will work completely fine with a level 7.

It is very recommended you invest in a level 10 cooldown gem for BF regardless of your build.

LW is the center of your rotation, and for 5 Spender specifically, it is important to match the level of this gem to that of your BF. This ensures a smoother sequence of skills.

This is not mandatory but noticeably smoother

Swiftness variants don’t need to worry as much about this gem.

Recommended to be as high as your BF gem for 5 Spender players.

Following this, SSB is also important, mostly for 4 Spender (4/9/10) and 5 Spender players. This skill is used for various purposes from applying Movement/Attack Speed buffs to building meter, constantly.

As such it's usually wise to upgrade it past level 7, as it will give your rotation a more fluid feeling.

Leaving it at level 7 is fine, but 9+ will feel noticeably better.

Do I need the Wealth runes?

Short answer, yes.

Long answer is you really need at least 1 Wealth,  1 Wealth and 2 Wealth runes. It's very much ideal to have 2 Wealth runes.

Use the above linked calculator to figure out if your Wealths are enough

Is Raid Captain/Mass Increase good on Esoteric Flurry Striker?

Due to the uptime on the attack speed buff fromBlessing of the Wind, Mass Increase’s negative is barely noticeable in most builds, but you shouldn't run it on 5 spender.

As far as Raid Captain goes, you rely on said attack speed buff to cap out your movement speed and get the full attack bonus, which is sometimes annoying to deal with, but is more than playable

Does our rotation change if you have Lazenith+Umar card set??

Not really, we don't want to play around the Lazenith buff as it is an RNG proc, and micromanaging it usually leads to more harm than gain for your DPS.

Just focus on developing a sort of internal timer so you know when it's more or less of cooldown and can avoid doing random actions that will proc it too soon or too late such as auto attacks or SDK into the boss.

Don't worry if it falls off sync, it will naturally line up over the course of the fight due to fight mechanics.

Is 5 Spender really better than Deathblow?

It depends on the pilot, fight and luck. Extremely well played 5 Spender can, in fact, out DPS Deathblow, but it's usually more or less the same and played for its more dynamic and engaging playstyle.

Is Esoteric Flurry viable in endgame raids?

Yes
